A very special piece of historical art lined the corridor walls of Parliament’s Old Assembly building. The Keiskamma Tapestry is said to be 120 metres long. Kate Crane Briggs from Culture Connect SA speaks to #eNCA Courtesy #DStv403 CAPE TOWN - A very special piece of historical art lines the corridor walls of Parliament’s Old Assembly building. It is called the Keiskamma Tapestry and is said to be 120 metres long. This tapestry was embroidered by more than 100 Xhosa women from the Eastern Cape. READ: Parliament Fire | WATCH | ANC Chief Whip urges colleagues not to speculate The priceless piece of art tells the story of South Africa, starting with the Khoisan. It is feared the Keiskamma Tapestry went up in flames in the Parliament fire. Watch the video above for more details on this story